asting your money. The company that I was going to work with on mobile phones actually sold to EE again quite a while ago from multi-millions, that\'s America. Because i\'ve got balloons and that\'s far more fun. So it shook her hand we did a deal we came back to the UK and we had this amazing little item and again, we couldn\'t promote it by the use of video, we couldn\'t do anything else other than go knocking on doors and try to introduce this product to anyone that we thought could be interested in balloons and going back to the 80s we didn\'t have the party shops that we have today. Balloons what you could walk high streets for hours and not find a balloon they were still very much the confines of fair grounds and then it kind of a circus isn\'t that kind of place that we didn\'t really have a good grounding you go after because the industry didn\'t exist and that\'s what made it tremendously exciting 03:36 exciting because I had carte blanche to 03:38 pretty much do things that no one else was doing because at the time they were probably in the UK five wholesalers of balloons or balloon related products only five, fast forward to 2018 is probably a hundred and fifty-five trying to chase the same market. Yes we\'ve grown the industry but yeah we\'re now in a situation because of the success we created back then it really has become oversaturated. So came back to the UK into in 1980 whatever it was with this crappy piece of ribbon that pretty much gave them every penny I had to bring into the UK, it arrived by sea and kind of open these boxes and there I was you know boxes for the ribbons, a few balloons and no real market. So brought in the stands 04:18 from the UK who spent three months with us. And we\'re doing fun stuff like telemarketing which was never done in the UK at a time we\'re literally walking door-to-door knocking on doors.\r\n\r\n<strong>Interviewer:</strong> So you guys were doing knocking with because it blows my mind today with how you know I 