\'re wasting your money. The company that I was going to work with on mobile phones actually sold to EE again quite a while ago from multi-millions, that\'s America. Because i\'ve got balloons and that\'s far more fun. So it shook her hand we did a deal we came back to the UK and we had this amazing little item and again, we couldn\'t promote it by the use of video, we couldn\'t do anything else other than go knocking on doors and try to introduce this product to anyone that we thought could be interested in balloons and going back to the 80s we didn\'t have the party shops that we have today. Balloons what you could walk high streets for hours and not find a balloon they were still very much the confines of fair grounds and then it kind of a circus isn\'t that kind of place that we didn\'t really have a good grounding you go after because the industry didn\'t exist and that\'s what made it tremendously exciting 03:36 exciting because I had carte blanche to 03:38 pretty much do things that no one else was doing because at the time they were probably in the UK five <a href=\"https://www.gointernational.co.uk/EZ/Balloon-Wholesaler\">wholesalers of balloons</a> or balloon related products only five, fast forward to 2018 is probably a hundred and fifty-five trying to chase the same market. Yes we\'ve grown the industry but yeah we\'re now in a situation because of the success we created back then it really has become oversaturated. So came back to the UK into in 1980 whatever it was with this crappy piece of ribbon that pretty much gave them every penny I had to bring into the UK, it arrived by sea and kind of open these boxes and there I was you know boxes for the ribbons, a few balloons and no real market. So brought in the stands 04:18 from the UK who spent three months with us. And we\'re doing fun stuff like telemarketing which was never done in the UK at a time we\'re literally walking door-to-door knocking on doors.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong> So you guys were doing knocking with because it blows my mind today with how you know I interact with us like okay buy something I go to Amazon or Ebay I go online, you know. Or I go into of course a shot from time to time but this Wow. So telesales and daughters or 04:44with the ribbon or with the other products also.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong> It was attached to the balloon actually put at one for you i\'ve still got a few thousand in the warehouse but next time we talk i\'ll have some talking ribbons with me. They were so great we didn\'t sell out. But it was an introduction to market and as I said we were given carte blanche that we wanted there were no rules and so we try anything, we weren\'t scared of failing and the product really did need to be demoed. It was something that I had to put into your hands and to do it, to actually get the full benefit. So trying to do that with a leaflet drop or anything like that just wouldn\'t have worked.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong> Gotcha.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong> And from there we approached to manufacturers in the UK they were actually they\'re American but they had small bases in the UK. In fact one of the biggest ones operated from a garage in London back then that\'s how small the industry was and saying well you know this is who we are this is what we\'d like to do, would you consider talking to us? And the answer was no they closed with order. Who was this guy who knew absolutely nothing about the industry suddenly wanted to do all this stuff and so to increase our balloon product range every Friday, still Friday I used to grab a virgin airways flight from Heathrow Airport, fly across the USA and go to the wholesaler there and literally come back with probably 20 cases of balloons. \r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong> You\'ve been on a journey, haven\'t you? Sorry to interrupt you, but this is incredible. I didn\'t, so because looking for the benefit of the people listening i\'ve known George for about six months and I got introduced to Go International as an e-commerce driven business because I knew that there was an online store and to hear this back story the idea of there being telesales, door-to-door, of the fire, this is incredible I\'m just blown away keep, sort of keep going. So we\'re on the you\'re on a virgin flight, I think well you\'re headed off to the States anyway.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong> Absolutely, and so yeah we were going back with I think at the very peak we were coming back with I would stay 30 cases of balloons on the Monday morning flight and I needed three Porter\'s to get them off the off the plane and to carry them through customs for us.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong> It sounds own being in India dude.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong> We had such a great villa, that was just me and I had such a great relationship with Virgin Atlantic that the deal was that if I did their parties for them free of charge then let me take all this stuff free of charge. So yeah we had porters carrying through and people like looking at me thinking what the hell\'s this guy got in these boxes. But it was great because yeah we did the New Year\'s party for verging back there I got to meet Richard Branson.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong> Wow, we need to come back to that bit of course that\'s going to be interesting to any. We\'ll do an episode just on meet Richard Branson because people gonna find that curious. \r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong> [inaudible 07:23 to 07:28] couple of photos. But yes this went on for about three or four months and then the main manufacturers you had divisions in the UK but kind of getting a little jittery they were saying you know this guy\'s come along all of a sudden we can see all this product in the marketplace, what\'s he doing. Is he just dumping it what\'s he doing. But we were really building relationships and it\'s something that i\'ve always loved I love to kind of go into something that\'s relatively new and show them ways of kind of increasing what they\'re doing.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong> And you showed that\'s getting a little bit lost today with how consumers are. I feel that like it\'s, I mean, you know I mean I come in kind of as a little bit of a layperson so one of the things I often think about is that I for example don\'t have any particular brand allegiance with Amazon, I go there because it\'s convenient but it\'s not about brand loyalty. It could be Amazon or ebay interchangeably and it sounds like the way that you operating then perhaps and I don\'t know if it\'s a challenge and we\'ll come and talk about that you know down the line in the kind of balloon and party marketplace today but certainly you talked about that one relationships. And I always think that you know it\'s not something that I have with Amazon and ebay and it sounds like something that\'s quite important to the growth in the history of well, George as well as go international and kind of your path.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong> If we\'re setting on website so we do what we do then it just becomes a price consideration. You suddenly come a pretty picture with the price lets as far as it goes. I still believe that the party industry is a specialist industry. I think that relationships are key to that. I loved in the beginning because I knew my accounts one-to-one I could pick up a phone speak from I saw them all. Now with over 16,000 accounts it\'s pretty difficult to call in and know them all personally. We used to do exhibitions we don\'t even bother with the exhibitions anymore because again it just becomes a very very expensive and shaking exercise. So from our perspective the ones that we really do the best with are the ones that know me and know my philosophy and understand that what I\'m trying to do. And it\'s also not about selling product, it\'s about how in the month 09:31 stand that they\'re not just buying the product on the wholesale basis, we\'re actually showing them what to do with our products.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong> Okay. And with I mean that would probably present quite a significant challenge with the because you were saying for example that you know there\'s over 5,000 accounts where I think you said 16 maybe. Yeah, okay. So how because I assume that your competitors as well as your accounts as well as everybody in the marketplace for example probably has the same issue. And I just wonder like do you have any, for example practical things that you still do that you find you know kind of make the difference. Or do you have any advice for someone who says well George it\'s very difficult for me to compete against town land 10:15 because you know Mary is just going off to buy a couple of things for her Christmas preparations. What would your advice be to someone who has that challenge?\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong> I think understand the market more than anything else. I the problem with the balloon industry it\'s so easy to get involved with. You literally you buy a packet of balloons off ebay if you want to you buy a cylinder of gas from ebay if you want to or Amazon. And all of a sudden you\'re a balloon decorator, you know you\'ve got the balloons you see you this is another problem the industry, it\'s very easy for people to look at how to do without really understanding what\'s really behind it. And for someone that spent their life trying to educate people and help people understand what the industry is really about, to see my customers being undercut because all the sudden Amazon ebay are literally dumping product on the market 20 News got a five-pound note in their pocket it makes it more challenging for them. Well I score exceedingly high points is where I\'m allowed to work with them, you know two years ago I was made chairman of an association called NOBAS, that\'s the National Association of balloon artists and suppliers. Through the education we provide there and through the interaction they have not directly with me but with the committee any other members as well. We can actually show them that if there is life beyond the high street and life beyond Amazon ebay Poundland and all the other discounters. It\'s becoming a specialist it\'s understanding your market, more importantly understanding your target audience. I\'ve got a mentoring program where I mentor students as well and they work with me and the results I have when I\'m allowed to help them understand where that what they need to do is phenomenal and that\'s where I grow sleeping 11:46 the challenges 2017 2018 year. Well probably be turn otherwise our best yet. But you have to work ten times harder to make it happen you know the dream was, it would go through this big stage, i\'ve kind of sit back in my chair and you know be on a beach somewhere enjoy myself and enjoying the fruits of my labor. But because of how the industry\'s changed because of the influx of competition and it\'s not always good competition, you\'re doing more to generate sometimes the same, sometimes less, sometimes a bit old 12:14.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong> Okay, okay again it sounds like the more, I mean God knows I\'m sure it was just as complex but in different ways perhaps you know in the 80s and when you were doing these things. Amazing. George I have a hundred and one more questions but actually for the interest of our audience I want to save some jewels for next week. So what I would love to finish up with is a final final question. What do you think is if there was one thing that some of these, you know some of your clients or accounts could do that they\'re perhaps not doing today to help differentiate themselves from you know you could about the Amazon dumping, the ebay dumping, what would you say is one practical thing that they could do that could help, you know maybe change things?\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong> I\'m a great believer in the power of five in you become who you mix with. And as entrepreneurs and small business owners we always believe we\'re on our own. Who do we turn to the good helpful advice, so what\'s the real reason people are offering us whatever they\'re offering us is it and what\'s in it for me scenario which regrettably most of times it is or are they actually looking at helping us grow. Again I\'m gonna go back to NABAS. Although I\'m kind of really promoting Go at the moment. I think NABAS is a key reason that I got involved with this because we\'re bringing people together who are like-minded and the interaction that we create with these members and we also do with the do customers 13:38 as well it\'s phenomenal. When they start talking to people who are in the same predicament with the same issues you realize you\'re not isolated, pretty much every retailer and every decorator out there has the same issues. They will have the same problems how do I, where do I go, what do I do. And by bringing them together it\'s amazing how those problems can be solved. But my power of five is I always like to think that you should have five go-to people. You should always have these people that either your 14:06 relatives or your friends whatever. But five people who are experts in areas you are not an expert in and the people are willing to give hard and take and they\'re pretty hard to find. But when you find this right set of people it totally turns around your business. When you realize that there\'s someone else that really asks you back and it has good helpful advice that can help you grow it turns your business on its head.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong> Okay, no George I think that\'s amazing advice and I think that the end message I\'d like to need to anyone of this listening is George is one of those people for you potentially. So Google George Go International or George NABAS Go International, George balloons Go International, any of those variations i\'ll also of course include the links. But George thank you so much and to everybody listening. See you next week.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong> Thank you everyone.', 'Balloon Industry Insights With Go International and George Oustayiannis - Episode 1', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '219-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-06-13 11:15:34', '2018-06-13 10:15:34', '', 219, 'https://www.gointernational.co.uk/blog/219-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
