(231, 1, '2018-06-21 10:06:49', '2018-06-21 09:06:49', '<iframe width=\"644\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/AyGy6_hhSVk\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"autoplay; encrypted-media\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n<h2>Video Transcription</h2>\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nGuys and ladies, welcome back to journey with Go International, we\'ve got of course George again. Last week George, we were talking about the kind of inception of you into this world of balloons starting life as a broker and then of course moving into the world of balloons. and I really wanted to kind of pick up upon some of the interesting parts of the journey we\'ve not heard all of it but let\'s begin by in the last time we spoke you specifically mentioned the first ever product that you had shipped by air sea or land, it took forever basically to get to the UK. and I think it was a talking ribbon that you spoke of and that you were selling this product potentially door-to-door and doing telesales. Do you have it with you by any chance, because I\'d absolutely love to see it.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nYeah, absolutely I scoured the warehouse it took me an hour to find them and but I was determined to find some of these for you and who knows this could be the start the resurgence of the talking balloon. So, here is the product which is a very thin piece of plastic it\'s about two foot long. Which was the birth of Go International in fact back then we talked we called ourselves Go International Stroke Talking Balloons. so this is what we have, it is like a piece of ribbon, it\'s approximately two foot long, it has grooves on one side, I actually attached a couple of to a balloon for you so I can demonstrate the product. You attach the ribbon onto the back of the balloon you would use your thumbnail as a needle this one says happy birthday. And one of them makes it a laughing balloon. So this is a talking balloon, and I’m sure you can see with that product alone I was set to make my fame and fortune and never have to worry about a bill in my life again because they would fly out the door and secure the future of George and Stanley forever and ever. Regrettably, that wasn\'t the case, we are very very British in how we sell, we still are even though we\'ve evolved tremendously products like this demo products especially are the sole domain in my opinion of the Americans, they know how to sell like you wouldn\'t believe. When I first saw this product in a shopping mall in the States the kind of interest it created, the interaction that the demonstrators were having with their customers was phenomenal and of course I thought replicate that in the UK, but it\'s very very different when you have the confidence of an American professional seller jumping in front of you and presenting themselves with a bunch of balloons and started to play this for you and getting the interact the Americans are used to that. whereas us in the UK folks have been someone on the shoulder saying, “Excuse me would you like to hear a talking balloon?” And most of the comments weren\'t exactly something I\'d like to repeat on air. So that was really the start of talking balloons it was a hard sell but it introduced us into something which I could see the potential in and that\'s how we really grew the product range from there. In the beginning most of these suppliers that were based or most of the manufacturers especially based in the UK and ready to worth talking about had a very small network of five distributors, we didn\'t want anymore. it was a close-knit network where they wanted to kind of protect each other and protect what they had. You fast forward 25 plus years we\'ve now got 155 distributors of the original five back then only two of us remain because the industry has, I\'d like to say evolve but it\'s changed, it\'s changed beyond all recognition. It used to be very very difficult to get involved in this industry as a supplier as an approved supplier because I think we had to prove ourselves and our apprenticeship and our route to market. These days anyone with a few foot of wall space can quite easily become a distributor in this industry and then more and more are. It\'s become not necessarily a fast track but it\'s become a nice introduction to a market which is growing it\'s still growing phenomenally well, but I think it\'s changed from where it was which is a nice kind of close knit specialist market into a mass market now where the priorities become making a profit rather than the party being growing an industry.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nOkay, okay interesting. and well you mentioned a couple of keywords that were really interesting. You didn\'t use the word, well no, you use evolved, changed, that\'s the first thing I\'d like to talk about and then the I think five distributors then it\'s grown to one hundred and fifty plus and only two I think you said from the originals remain. So let\'s talk first of all about the evolved versus changed, could you kind of unpack what you mean and what that means for the balloon industry and what that meant for you?\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nYeah from the five started I think it was a case of having a virgin industry where there wasn\'t that much going on, we were growing at a relatively comfortable pace we were seeing great sales figures we\'re doing more stuff like exhibiting we\'re all doing the same stuff give or take the next  degree. We were more proactive in the online market online, in the telesales marketing side of things and doing stuff that others weren’t doing. The industry is pretty much owned by American manufacturers and without making it sound too derogatory, the Americans want to see sales figures they\'re driven by sales figures. and sometimes you don\'t really care how that happens as long as I see great sales figures, and they wanted to protect what they had in the UK market because they saw UK as a tremendous springboard to the rest of Europe, which it has been, and that has been at the cost of really keeping that specialist element of what we do. Our biggest market was really the decorating market, we had guys and girls out there doing weddings and themed events and it was a very specialist thing in a sense of that come along and learn how to do this stuff they did training. Fast-forward now we have how-to videos on YouTube, so you\'ve got the general public looking at YouTube videos which I\'m totally against I don\'t think we should have How-to videos at all because it is something we should try and protect. The Americans still want to see the growth of the market. so again they\'re consistently putting pressure on us to kind of up our figures and get more product out there, a typical example is only just before Christmas, there\'s a great brand of latex that\'s come to the UK, it\'s been here before but it\'s actually being much more than the major manufacturers now, and but rather than giving it to the specialist manufacturers or the, sorry, the  specialist wholesalers to play with it, you have a party specialist know the industry that know the decorators are trained on a regular basis. They give it to a wholesaler that really is more interested in volume sales, so again they\'ve had exclusives for three months, it\'s being made available to a select few in the next month or so. but that\'s what I kind of struggle with the fact that I\'m trying to promote and protect an industry and keep it professional but with the influx of noise, be it Facebook, be it Instagram be it whatever the influx of noise and the influx of interest. it\'s not always being protected the way it should be. we\'re taking and of course we\'re all here to make it and make a living there\'s no doubt about it. but we\'re putting profit above the art and I still believe balloon is an art. The association is balloon artists and suppliers, it\'s an art form that should be built on expanded on, our training should continue to evolve and it\'s difficult to do that when anyone with a 5-pound mo can go online and <a href=\"https://www.gointernational.co.uk/Balloons\">buy balloons</a> make a little decorator.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nIt sounds like it\'s become a really complex marketplace with the advent as you said of How-to videos was an interesting one that you mentioned the preferential treatment that there is sometimes of sales, volume sales, above and beyond the specialism that is you know, the balloon industry. and how do you, I assume deal with perhaps people that say well George, you know do we change with the times? Invariably some element of us has to but there must be that invariable kind of paradigm of the how two videos are out there, the volume sales. Sso how is it that someone kind of in this marketplace can adjust and what have you done because I assume of course it you know telesales is something that doesn\'t work, I don\'t know it doesn\'t work the industry but how have you had to adapt and what can you do to both adapt but still preserve some of those core values?\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nWell we still continue to grow which is great, you know you and you\'re out continuing to grow in strength and continue to grow our market share and that really is by I would say is we educate but it really is again we touched on it briefly last week it really is about relationships. If we become again I think I mentioned before this comparison website where we\'ve got a product and you\'ve got a product and all it is a couple of pictures in the price break down, then the cheapest price always wins. But if we are actually selling the concept of what we are, what we do, what we\'re trying to achieve, more importantly if the relationship doesn\'t stop with the selling of the product but starts with the selling of the product that\'s the first interaction you have with your customer. If they generally see the efforts that you are putting into trying to help their business grow, there you do score brownie points. Why does everyone go self-employed, why does everyone want to be their own boss? The two words always come to mind when you want to do this is freedom, and money. How\'s that working a helpful with you cut a path going different directions all of a sudden your freedoms gone, you\'re working more as than you ever have before, you\'re the bottle washing, you\'re the toilet cleaner, you\'re everything you\'re meant to be. When it comes to money, most people it\'s industry actually take a dip in money when it comes to starting a business in it and initially, the dropout rate is in ease of 92 percent in the first year because it\'s so easy to get involved with. They see the great stuff being done, they see the huge corporations doing tremendously well and they want a chunk for that, but they don\'t realize that there\'s a lot of work involved as well, so going self-employed and going into the party industry we\'ve got a number of people at the point you in their directions been tremendously well but we get to be the vast majority are still dabbling and it because a double as market. as we said you buy a few balloons, you buy a bottle of gas, all of a sudden your balloon decorators, you do your friends, you do your relatives weddings or whatever for them and then all the sudden you realize that what do I do next, where does the marketing come into it, how do I promote my business. Then that\'s always been our strength, we always look at the marketing of your business, we always try and help our customers look at what\'s next, rather than just kind of say well here\'s your product see you later goodbye now and that\'s why we have continued to grow of course we don\'t win them all or always people out there shopping on price and nothing but price. and we gradually in most of the cases they are the ones that are part of that nineteen ninety five percent that fail in the first year. because any business you\'re going to it\'s not purely balloons, it has changed, it has everything is becoming about I think the best thing that can give you is the analogy that I was told usually when I was studying law. I was told that the right person doesn\'t always win, it\'s the person with the best story that wins. So it\'s learning to tell your best story and everyone should have a best story. If you\'re doing something you\'ve got to, and again I think there is something out there called what\'s your why, you\'ve got to know what your why is and understanding that and I certainly understand what my way is like to tell you exactly why I do this but understanding what you why is and understanding what the groundwork you need to do and also that ongoing development that meets their happen I\'m not just looking at a video but just going out there and spending money and doing the legwork and learning your art learning your trainings done, and that\'s what we can continually kind of pushing in what I do especially is let\'s train you, let\'s help you, let\'s not just give you the product, let\'s give you the marketing ideas, let\'s teach you how to do something like this, let\'s teach you how to do something like an email campaign. There is you\'ve got to have different pillars within your business and so many depend on just that one pillar and when it starts to teter, it\'s easy to lose confidence in whose direction.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nWhat was the way that your surname is of course the dead giveaway Oustayiannis, what was the way that you gave to your parents, when you said mom I\'m leaving my job to be a broker and I\'m gonna go in sell balloons. What was your why then?\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nI think my why\'s why you disowning me. Yeah from a traditional Greek family from where I come from especially you have two options, you either become a doctor and when you become a lawyer. If you\'re not that bright you can become an accountant and get away with it and it gives some grea