 we had to prove ourselves and our apprenticeship and our route to market. These days anyone with a few foot of wall space can quite easily become a distributor in this industry and then more and more are. It\'s become not necessarily a fast track but it\'s become a nice introduction to a market which is growing it\'s still growing phenomenally well, but I think it\'s changed from where it was which is a nice kind of close knit specialist market into a mass market now where the priorities become making a profit rather than the party being growing an industry.\n\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\nOkay, okay interesting. and well you mentioned a couple of keywords that were really interesting. You didn\'t use the word, well no, you use evolved, changed, that\'s the first thing I\'d like to talk about and then the I think five distributors then it\'s grown to one hundred and fifty plus and only two I think you said from the originals remain. So let\'s talk first of all about the evolved versus changed, could you kind of unpack what you mean and what that means for the balloon industry and what that meant for you?\n\n<strong>George:</strong>\nYeah from the five started I think it was a case of having a virgin industry where there wasn\'t that much going on, we were growing at a relatively comfortable pace we were seeing great sales figures we\'re doing more stuff like exhibiting we\'re all doing the same stuff give or take the next  degree. We were more proactive in the online market online, in the telesales marketing side of things and doing stuff that others weren’t doing. The industry is pretty much owned by American manufacturers and without making it sound too derogatory, the Americans want to see sales figures they\'re driven by sales figures. and sometimes you don\'t really care how that happens as long as I see great sales figures, and they wanted to protect what they had in the UK market because they saw UK as a tremendous springboard to the rest of Europe, which it has been, and that has been at the cost of really keeping that specialist element of what we do. Our biggest market was really the decorating market, we had guys and girls out there doing weddings and themed events and it was a very specialist thing in a sense of that come along and learn how to do this stuff they did training. Fast-forward now we have how-to videos on YouTube, so you\'ve got the general public looking at YouTube videos which I\'m totally against I don\'t think we should have How-to videos at all because it is something we should try and protect. The Americans still want to see the growth of the market. so again they\'re consistently putting pressure on us to kind of up our figures and get more product out there, a typical example is only just before Christmas, there\'s a great brand of latex that\'s come to the UK, it\'s been here before but it\'s actually being much more than the major manufacturers now, and but rather than giving it to the specialist manufacturers or the, sorry, the  specialist wholesalers to play with it, you have a party specialist know the industry that know the decorators are trained on a regular basis. They give it to a wholesaler that really is more interested in volume sales, so again they\'ve had exclusives for three months, it\'s being made available to a select few in the next month or so. but that\'s what I kind of struggle with the fact that I\'m trying to promote and protect an industry and keep it professional but with the influx of noise, be it Facebook, be it Instagram be it whatever the influx of noise and the influx of interest. it\'s not always being protected the way it should be. we\'re taking and of course we\'re all here to make it and make a living there\'s no doubt about it. but we\'re putting profit above the art and I still believe balloon is an art. The association is balloon artists and suppliers, it\'s an art form that should be built on expanded on, our training should continue to evolve and it\'s dif