 was fine but as you progress up the ladder and you\'re more seated behind your desk, I wasn\'t enjoying that too much. so my why was look you know let me fly, let me do what I want to do. I was still young enough at the time but if I did fail drastically I would still have a door anywhere I could go back. Dad still hoped I’d go back even when I hit my late years, but I didn\'t and it didn\'t really it didn\'t really matter what we achieved from my parents perspective, the are tremendously proud obviously they are.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nYeah, yeah. \r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nSo they wanted a different title to give me in church other than Balloon Seller I guess, so my big why is because I had to, I had to prove that I could do this on my own. Growing up again as a Greek family we were tremendously protected, we went, we, yes it\'s a long story but very few.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nWe\'re gonna make up on this story because I\'m fascinated especially just from my own perspective as being in a British Indian and wondering how that has all played out in respective, you know role models and you know what your children have gone on to do, successful lawyers, successful GP, fantastic. and also potentially, you know how you introduce yourself at the various dinner parties where there are your balloons at the events that you do go to and you know how you\'ve become to be known in the industry. Our 15 minutes is up today George that was fantastic. What I\'d like to finish up with is for you..\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nYou want to buy some talking balloons don’t you? You want to buy your place in order for talking balloons.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nCan I place an order for talking balloons and could you also in a kind of 60-second kind of pitch what\'s your number one piece of advice to fend off against that failure rate that you spoke about in your first year, for someone who says “I like the look at this I think I could make some money here.” What would you give the advice to someone who approaches you that, you know just set up shop and they\'re eager or they\'re just talking sales figures with you?\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nI\'m going to go back to NABAS, that\'s they join NABAS, the National Association of Balloon Artists and Suppliers for the simple reason we\'re such a strong support mechanism within that group. that all those burning questions you have in a very, very beginning are answered for you,  and that\'s what we want to do, we want to kind of evolve through training. We want to immerse people in a group of people that have been on that journey before them probably at the same time of them, that can really help them grow and really give them the support that they need in the very beginning.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nYeah, okay makes complete sense. So everybody if you\'re listening, we\'ll be back next week for another 15 minutes on the journey of Go International. Thank you George again and bring another prop yet again for next time that was my favorite part.', 'Balloon Industry Insights With Go International and George Oustayiannis – Episode 2', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '231-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-06-21 10:12:56', '2018-06-21 09:12:56', '', 231, 'https://www.gointernational.co.uk/blog/231-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
