(235, 1, '2018-06-26 14:33:48', '2018-06-26 13:33:48', '<iframe width=\"643\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/dnIsRPzCxUs\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"autoplay; encrypted-media\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nHi everybody welcome back to episode three of A Journey With Go International I’m back with George again today. George I\'d love for you today to talk to me about for example one of the greatest challenges that you faced in your business and how you adjust it to that.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nEvery day or just in general?\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nI think talk about, let\'s focus on a particular crisis moment in your business perhaps where you thought my god I\'m not sure if I\'m going to survive the end of month or the end of year and what you did in that position to kind of turn things around.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nI know you like props so I got a prop. I\'ll explain what is it in a minute. It\'s about 2000 printed on there.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nLet\'s do this every episode.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nWell I can’t get you a prop every single episode. I think the big challenge was probably the biggest was probably 1999, as we are approaching the Millennium and we\'re told the Millennium will be the biggest party in the history so we\'re all importing product like you wouldn\'t believe in the Far East and I\'ve got about five million of these if you want any. It\'s got two thousand on there so if you want some clickers we have some. So yeah it was it was okay. It was nowhere near as good as it was going to be for anybody. If you remember or you\'re very very young, but whatever, hotels in London will be installed or initially priced a thousand pounds a night. As we got closer and closer to 1999, the 31st of December the hotel prices were tumbling down to 100 pounds a night some of the best hotels because it just wasn\'t happening. I spent New Year\'s eve in London in Jack London Square we\'re not going to see in the Millennium crying in my beer as I was looking oh yeah.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nI was there also a bit younger of course but I..\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nI stepped on you there were so many kids in the way I just kicked them out of the way,  I think you were probably one them.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nOne of many.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nAbsolutely. So I think it\'s always because if you want to set yourself up as being a leader in industry then you have to lead by example and you need the product there. So as your customers need that product then it\'s available to them so we did go heavy on millennium, it was still good it was still profitable but when I looked at all the stuff that was left of it at the end of it because it really didn\'t kick off the way it was. I think that\'s probably one of the biggest challenges we faced back then which was I would say it was a teaching moment but it was a sharp intake of breath when you look at the investment you made and exactly what that cost you to have sitting on your shelves. Plus a huge amount of space it took up in the warehouse at the time prior to being here, we had we still own them. We have five warehouses over in little village called Sheppard and they were totally stacked to the gunnels with millennium stuff. So you know we kind of opened up the boxes are broken down and so on what we could so it wasn\'t tremendously bad but it\'s those events because as a party specialist you always have to be ready for the big events, it would be a Christmas, be a new year, be a Valentine\'s Day coming up in just a little whiles time. And from the Go International perspective we represent 65 of the world\'s leading manufacturers as well as that design and manufacture much of our own stuff as well. So even if you don\'t see a Go badge on there I pretty much can guarantee that the leading wholesalers in the UK have something we\'ve had our hands on somewhere on the line. I’m always leading and making sure that that products to market be I think the biggest challenges that we have become a want it now market. Yes if we don\'t, we no longer believe in the deferred gratification, we want instant gratification. So we\'re not willing to wait for an item to come we had again another challenge but I had a call it was an email on Christmas Day, from an irate customer saying that she\'d waited in all day Christmas Day because she placed the order Christmas Eve and we promised the order would be with a guarantee next-day delivery. So of course we were in Christmas for her because her package didn\'t arrive Christmas Day. And this is where we\'re going now because of people\'s expectations because of the likes of Amazon where you place an order 10, 11 maybe midnight it\'s with you the next day. We\'re all being put under increasing pressure to have that product with that customer right now. And that\'s not just for retail customer where I say retail I mean end-user that\'s our retail customers as well. The actual shops are now leaving it much later to order when we started, again old school it was like I think I mentioned this very briefly again, it was wait 7 to 10 days for delivery we were quite happy for that. Every day that went by excited to see that order and we were waiting for it to come awake Mr. Postman to arrive with our package. Now it\'s placed an order at midnight and by 8:00 in the morning we\'re panicking thinking with our packages and you know what no one is pre-planning and because we represent so many manufacturers/ when you represent that many you can\'t possibly have 65 manufacturers products every single lining on your shelves. We\'d need a place twice the size of Wembley Stadium to do that. So our philosophy you always been we represent them if you want it, if it exists if it\'s in the UK we\'re gonna get it for you and we still do that. But we don\'t come across more and more why isn\'t it there, why haven\'t you got it now. So I think, I think from my perspective that probably is that the biggest challenge getting the message across and especially if you\'re a retailer and you\'re in this industry, kind of pre-planning your events a little better. If you\'ve got, if you know you\'ve got a customers wedding coming up tomorrow, you certainly don\'t order those products today. And I know more and more end-users, more and more brides are coming in with a smaller window of opportunity than ever before as well and they\'re only giving you six months to plan it they\'re coming in probably with a month or so. But it it\'s really planning ahead and again it\'s I understand why retailers can\'t do it because it\'s the investment involved with having all that on stuff on their shelves as well. So we\'ve got to be the middleman to make sure we can we can buffer that for them and protect them. But there\'s really no way around it. As we continue to grow as we take on more product from around the world, it\'s always gonna be a case of that is definitely my biggest challenge. How do I make sure that my customers are well protected and have the approach they need when they need them when we get to be they need them in half an hour\'s time.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nSo no, absolutely it makes sense. And I mean even like on high street stores I think it wasn\'t just even a week ago I was still seeing some posts Christmas stock that some of the high street stores were trying to shift and everything kind of was cut price. So what happens, I mean in those instances where because ecommerce businesses in general that sell product, what happens to unused stock where does it go, what do you do with that?\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nThere we are twenty years later and look.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nSo, this is what I do. \r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nThe joy of our events Christmas, Halloween, it\'s gonna come around in 12 months time. The downside is that you\'ve got 12 months worth of valuable stock that needs to be paid for there hasn\'t sold through but it\'s packed away and put on your shelf store the next year. So you are seeing more and more of this clearance as well where people I kind of panic selling sometimes a little before the event, sometimes it\'s little after event because our suppliers want to be paid whether we sell it or not but joy is at least we know that events going to come around in 12 months time again. So it\'s just kind of biting the bullet and realizing that you\'re not spending as much in 2018, they looking in 2017 because you\'re just going up on the shelves and pulling it all down, and putting it back out again.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nOkay, that does make sense. Thinking of celebrations, can you talk us through some particular products that tend to do well irrespective of the year so this is one product that will sell every Christmas regardless, and you know mothers that do Christmas with their two boys love this particular product. Is it, do you have some things that spring to mind examples of it?\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nObviously not talking balloons. The joy of our industry is everyday someone\'s birthday. So it\'s always going to be your bread and butter lines that\'s what really kind of keeps you ahead of the game I\'m floating. I\'m just knowing that everyone irrespective of who they are as a lot of birthday, so there\'s always a sales opportunity within that for absolutely everyone. The events we talk about the Valentine\'s Day which are coming up now, a really a shot in the arm. It\'s the additional boost of adrenaline for us because we\'re getting additional kind of rush of sales that have a kind of a two-week span for us where we\'re kind of pushing all out and doing well with it. But even those events now because we\'ve become absolutely saturated with so many people in the marketplace even our retailers who I can introduce you to many of them and I think  I\'ve kind of give me a few people to talk to as well so they can give you a grounding of the joys of retail too. They\'re not getting that same kind of rush that they used to be of course again it goes down to certainly people chasing the same market. A red heart, we had a customer literally five miles from us and on Valentine\'s Day they would have a queue literally you know 50 yards and it\'s no exaggeration a 50-yard queue of people queuing up to buy red foil balloons on Valentine\'s Day and they were busy from two days before putting the balloons in a box and having them ready for their customers, pre-taking pre-orders as well. Now it\'s just another day with probably a 20 percent boost because even Marks and Spencers even Tesco\'s even name one Matalan, they all want to get involved in this because it\'s a quick kind of again quick sale for them. So the rather than selling a balloon that my retailer should be selling for two pound 50 for example, you getting a red heart for a pound from somewhere else so they\'re kind of again devaluing the market which makes it difficult. And we\'re all prepared for this now so we don\'t go as nuts as we used to in Valentine\'s Day or anything else. We kind of know it\'s going to be okay but not the most amazing thing since sliced bread. And it\'s just adapting to that so I would say when it comes to our bread and butter lines it is the everyday, it\'s the birthday, it’s the christenings, it\'s the anniversaries, it\'s the weddings are always gonna happen irrespective of what else is out there.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nOkay, okay, okay now that does make him a lot of sense and I certainly thinking just about my own family and the continuous stream of the Indians, birthdays, events, it\'s like non-stop. So it makes a lot of sense that\'s the actual core consistency rather then I think okay Valentine\'s Day must be the best but actually no it\'s as you said the bread and butter. Talking then of events, are there some particular kind of singular events that have been kind of stand out like moments for Go International that you know have been, yeah just talk to me a little bit about a couple of the events that you guys have been involved in that have been interesting.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nI think Halloween. When we first started in Halloween there was literally nothing in the UK. It\'s seriously nothing, we weren’t Trick or Treating or anything. And we\'d probably be lucky to sell even from a wholesale perspective...\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nHang on, so we weren\'t trick-or-treaters that blows my mind as someone, okay let\'s pivot a little bit. Talk to me a little bit about that then and how that has changed the business because Halloween today is huge. So could you talk to me a little bit about your experience of the growth and development of Halloween as a celebrated festival in England?\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nAgain thank you USA. We follow the USA on all these things they certainly took the lead and again because of the advent of internet and more interaction with people who have seen what was out there and growing our market, but again going back to the very beginning I think we would not, we wouldn\'t sell more than a couple of hundred Halloween balloons, foil balloons and that was about it. You dress up, you probably get a broomstick, you\'d probably get a witch\'s hat but if you look at what\'s out there that\'s totally exploded, totally exploded, so Halloween on a consistent basis we\'ve seen growth. In 2017 maybe not so much because again we\'re going back to everyone jumping on the bandwagon and everyone here going into Poundlands even going into any of the supermarkets, their shelves were actually chock-a-block with Halloween. So regrettably up all retailers haven\'t had that same shot in the arm that they used to get from something like Halloween. If it\'s smart and they\'re buying smart they can certainly still make an impact in their in their area but overall again it\'s another item that we\'ve seen start for absolutely zero skyrocketing to something you wouldn\'t believe and all some come not necessary crashing down for a sudden finding a level where we\'re just kind of doing okay with it.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nOkay, okay. Now Halloween, Halloween, Halloween, it blows my mind then. It sounds it sounds like the Americans are a little bit of, because they\'ve come up in a couple of our conversations when we were talking in regards to sales, we talked about Halloween and at the event, has the, is it fair then to say in the balloon industry that the Americans have been kind of the, have paved the way they\'ve been the pave makers, if you want from it.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nOh I\'m a shadow, whether it comes to who the leading manufacturers are, one of the leading trainers are, they\'re definitely all American and still are there are. Three probably, yeah three powerhouses at the moment which dominate the market they pretty much lead where we\'re going, what we\'re doing what the colors are going to be and we kind of follow and say thank you very much for the lead really.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nOkay, okay it\'s fascinating to me. What about then on the continent? What is the balloon market like outside of the UK? Because we\'ve just had a UK in kind of American focus really.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nI think the UK, we mentioned this last time has become a springboard for Europe for all that manufactures and it\'s been a good springboard and the joy of, I think the continent is where we were maybe 15-20 years ago where they\'re still developing their markets are still growing their markets and those who are involved are having an amazing time, it\'s like the gold rush where it\'s brand-new stuff everyone\'s being involved in and doing well because it\'s not involved in the way it has in the UK they\'re certainly on experiencing over saturation of the marketplace. So seeing more growth if you look at a growth curve, we\'re seeing more growth in Europe than we are in the UK right now. Because they\'re being allowed to do a week in the beginning go out there try new stuff and introduced the product to new markets. So absolutely Europe is a tremendous market for all of us.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nAnd is that for then someone who\'s coming you into the industry would you almost say that, you know the mainland Europe is a really interesting space. Do you, have you are there any particular adjustments you\'d need to make as a UK-based seller of balloons if you\'re trying to market to the French the Spanish, I\'ve got no idea really.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nYou know there are products out there especially Spanish because of the Spanish-American link as well and so there\'s lots of printed product which was fits into the Spanish market, we have birthday balloons in French. So if the market once said it can be produced very easily, it\'s never going to be an issue to do that. The other joy of Europe at the moment of course with BRX, the exchange rate, the euro to the pound ratio is really favored the European market so they\'re buying a lot more than they were before too and getting great prices right now.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nOkay that makes sense, okay. Final question, George before I love and leave you today. Can you, and well we\'ll talk about this in a lot further depth. What is thinking of the future talking about Europe and its growth curve, could you kind of give me what you think are a couple of like the trends of what you think the next 18, 24 to 36 months is going to look like in the balloon industry in general?\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nAnd you see a lot of consolidation, regrettably I can see numbers dwindling in respect to who the current players are and who they\'re going to be in year 12 might, well net 12 to 18 months down the line. Last year we saw two major manufacturers in their day, I\'m sorry two major wholesalers in their day to disappear off the face of the earth, they stopped trading. And it didn\'t even raise a blip on the Richter scale, you know once upon a time when companies of that size wins it will cause a problem. But it\'s been diluted extent now where no one has ultimate power. No one has that kind of ability to put that kind of strength on the market where they missed anymore. And because of that I think we\'re where I see it going is amalgamations, I see people working closer together and I see people obviously disappearing as well because they can\'t cope with what\'s happening out there. It\'ll be more streamlined. We are going to see the power players continue to dominate and kind of instill their brand, belief and what we should be doing on us and us having to kind of to a certain extent toe the line because if we don\'t or we do need them on our side, then again more problems arise. And so overall, I\'d say it\'s not necessarily gloomy as such but I definitely think that the changes we\'re going to see in the next 12 to 18 months and you\'ll be far more drastic than the changes we\'ve seen over the past 30 years.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nIs there then perhaps an opportunity for, is the key then to go specialist, if you\'re someone who\'s new is entering the market. Should you not enter the market at all because of the incumbents? So what\'s the advice then for someone who\'s like George\'s all these different kinds of products, there\'s all these suppliers. I know when I get into it but I don\'t I\'m not sure on my angle.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nOkay. We\'re very guilty of down selling rather than up selling. So if a newbie comes to us they want to spend and we\'ve had it many many times you want to spend a couple of grand with us and they want to kiss out of shop and they want to buy everything they possibly can. We always kind of down selling and we won\'t let them buy all the items they want to buy. We want them to understand their specific demographics and what they\'re trying to achieve. It\'s daunting to go into a into a wholesalers and look at all this stuff, all this kind of pretty sparkly stuff and know what\'s right for you. And so we\'re very conscious of making sure and to help them on their way making sure they\'re not one of these 90 to 95 failure rates in the first year. We\'re very conscious of making them understand that they need to know what their marketplace is. You know I don\'t believe this bad business is, I really don\'t I believe there\'s bad business owners. Because they haven\'t done due diligence they haven\'t looked into really what they want to do make them so many times it\'s just a whim they come into this because it\'s easy to get the get involved with. Then actually looking at what they want to achieve. So it\'s putting that horse behind you for a minute and putting the cart in front and of switching things around and then flipping things on their head and try to understand what are you trying to do in this industry, what are you coming to do, are you coming just to enter an industry because someone down the road has an amazing shop and I seem to be very very busy and they seem to be doing all the right things so you want a bit of that action. Are you doing that because you have a genuine passion for creativity and it\'s something that you can see a niché for? Have you done your homework? Have you research the area? Do you know if the demographics around you are kind of the older generation so they\'re looking for, here if you go to esport for example, if you go to esport it\'s like a retirement home in the UK. It\'s pointless going down there and having lots of Disney characters and Mickey and Mini and all the other stuff. Because you should be looking at anniversaries perhaps, you should be looking at something that fits in that market. So is it really is doing your homework before even spending a penny understanding who you looking to sell to.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nOkay, that sounds really senseable of when it sounds like someone who\'s has an understanding of course it has been through kind of the wars and the ups and downs. So everybody I guess the lesson here of course is do your homework, pick a particular demographic be excited nonetheless but really think about your positioning. Thank you George. I will see you, next week guys.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nThank you everybody. ', 'A Journey With Go International George Oustayiannis - Episode 3', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'journey-go-international-george-oustayiannis-episode-3', '', '', '2018-08-29 16:57:25', '2018-08-29 15:57:25', '', 0, 'https://www.gointernational.co.uk/blog/?p=235', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(236, 1, '2018-06-26 14:33:48', '2018-06-26 13:33:48', '<iframe width=\"643\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/dnIsRPzCxUs\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"autoplay; encrypted-media\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nHi everybody welcome back to episode three of A Journey With Go International I’m back with George again today. George I\'d love for you today to talk to me about for example one of the greatest challenges that you faced in your business and how you adjust it to that.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nEvery day or just in general?\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nI think talk about, let\'s focus on a particular crisis moment in your business perhaps where you thought my god I\'m not sure if I\'m going to survive the end of month or the end of year and what you did in that position to kind of turn things around.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nI know you like props so I got a prop. I\'ll explain what is it in a minute. It\'s about 2000 printed on there.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nLet\'s do this every episode.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nWell I can’t get you a prop every single episode. I think the big challenge was probably the biggest was probably 1999, as we are approaching the Millennium and we\'re told the Millennium will be the biggest party in the history so we\'re all importing product like you wouldn\'t believe in the Far East and I\'ve got about five million of these if you want any. It\'s got two thousand on there so if you want some clickers we have some. So yeah it was it was okay. It was nowhere near as good as it was going to be for anybody. If you remember or you\'re very very young, but whatever, hotels in London will be installed or initially priced a thousand pounds a night. As we got closer and closer to 1999, the 31st of December the hotel prices were tumbling down to 100 pounds a night some of the best hotels because it just wasn\'t happening. I spent New Year\'s eve in London in Jack London Square we\'re not going to see in the Millennium crying in my beer as I was looking oh yeah.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nI was there also a bit younger of course but I..\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nI stepped on you there were so many kids in the way I just kicked them out of the way,  I think you were probably one them.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nOne of many.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nAbsolutely. So I think it\'s always because if you want to set yourself up as being a leader in industry then you have to lead by example and you need the product there. So as your customers need that product then it\'s available to them so we did go heavy on millennium, it was still good it was still profitable but when I looked at all the stuff that was left of it at the end of it because it really didn\'t kick off the way it was. I think that\'s probably one of the biggest challenges we faced back then which was I would say it was a teaching moment but it was a sharp intake of breath when you look at the investment you made and exactly what that cost you to have sitting on your shelves. Plus a huge amount of space it took up in the warehouse at the time prior to being here, we had we still own them. We have five warehouses over in little village called Sheppard and they were totally stacked to the gunnels with millennium stuff. So you know we kind of opened up the boxes are broken down and so on what we could so it wasn\'t tremendously bad but it\'s those events because as a party specialist you always have to be ready for the big events, it would be a Christmas, be a new year, be a Valentine\'s Day coming up in just a little whiles time. And from the Go International perspective we represent 65 of the world\'s leading manufacturers as well as that design and manufacture much of our own stuff as well. So even if you don\'t see a Go badge on there I pretty much can guarantee that the leading wholesalers in the UK have something we\'ve had our hands on somewhere on the line. I’m always leading and making sure that that products to market be I think the biggest challenges that we have become a want it now market. Yes if we don\'t, we no longer believe in the deferred gratification, we want instant gratification. So we\'re not willing to wait for an item to come we had again another challenge but I had a call it was an email on Christmas Day, from an irate customer saying that she\'d waited in all day Christmas Day because she placed the order Christmas Eve and we promised the order would be with a guarantee next-day delivery. So of course we were in Christmas for her because her package didn\'t arrive Christmas Day. And this is where we\'re going now because of people\'s expectations because of the likes of Amazon where you place an order 10, 11 maybe midnight it\'s with you the next day. We\'re all being put under increasing pressure to have that product with that customer right now. And that\'s not just for retail customer where I say retail I mean end-user that\'s our retail customers as well. The actual shops are now leaving it much later to order when we started, again old school it was like I think I mentioned this very briefly again, it was wait 7 to 10 days for delivery we were quite happy for that. Every day that went by excited to see that order and we were waiting for it to come awake Mr. Postman to arrive with our package. Now it\'s placed an order at midnight and by 8:00 in the morning we\'re panicking thinking with our packages and you know what no one is pre-planning and because we represent so many manufacturers/ when you represent that many you can\'t possibly have 65 manufacturers products every single lining on your shelves. We\'d need a place twice the size of Wembley Stadium to do that. So our philosophy you always been we represent them if you want it, if it exists if it\'s in the UK we\'re gonna get it for you and we still do that. But we don\'t come across more and more why isn\'t it there, why haven\'t you got it now. So I think, I think from my perspective that probably is that the biggest challenge getting the message across and especially if you\'re a retailer and you\'re in this industry, kind of pre-planning your events a little better. If you\'ve got, if you know you\'ve got a customers wedding coming up tomorrow, you certainly don\'t order those products today. And I know more and more end-users, more and more brides are coming in with a smaller window of opportunity than ever before as well and they\'re only giving you six months to plan it they\'re coming in probably with a month or so. But it it\'s really planning ahead and again it\'s I understand why retailers can\'t do it because it\'s the investment involved with having all that on stuff on their shelves as well. So we\'ve got to be the middleman to make sure we can we can buffer that for them and protect them. But there\'s really no way around it. As we continue to grow as we take on more product from around the world, it\'s always gonna be a case of that is definitely my biggest challenge. How do I make sure that my customers are well protected and have the approach they need when they need them when we get to be they need them in half an hour\'s time.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nSo no, absolutely it makes sense. And I mean even like on high street stores I think it wasn\'t just even a week ago I was still seeing some posts Christmas stock that some of the high street stores were trying to shift and everything kind of was cut price. So what happens, I mean in those instances where because ecommerce businesses in general that sell product, what happens to unused stock where does it go, what do you do with that?\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nThere we are twenty years later and look.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nSo, this is what I do. \r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nThe joy of our events Christmas, Halloween, it\'s gonna come around in 12 months time. The downside is that you\'ve got 12 months worth of valuable stock that needs to be paid for there hasn\'t sold through but it\'s packed away and put on your shelf store the next year. So you are seeing more and more of this clearance as well where people I kind of panic selling sometimes a little before the event, sometimes it\'s little after event because our suppliers want to be paid whether we sell it or not but joy is at least we know that events going to come around in 12 months time again. So it\'s just kind of biting the bullet and realizing that you\'re not spending as much in 2018, they looking in 2017 because you\'re just going up on the shelves and pulling it all down, and putting it back out again.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nOkay, that does make sense. Thinking of celebrations, can you talk us through some particular products that tend to do well irrespective of the year so this is one product that will sell every Christmas regardless, and you know mothers that do Christmas with their two boys love this particular product. Is it, do you have some things that spring to mind examples of it?\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nObviously not talking balloons. The joy of our industry is everyday someone\'s birthday. So it\'s always going to be your bread and butter lines that\'s what really kind of keeps you ahead of the game I\'m floating. I\'m just knowing that everyone irrespective of who they are as a lot of birthday, so there\'s always a sales opportunity within that for absolutely everyone. The events we talk about the Valentine\'s Day which are coming up now, a really a shot in the arm. It\'s the additional boost of adrenaline for us because we\'re getting additional kind of rush of sales that have a kind of a two-week span for us where we\'re kind of pushing all out and doing well with it. But even those events now because we\'ve become absolutely saturated with so many people in the marketplace even our retailers who I can introduce you to many of them and I think  I\'ve kind of give me a few people to talk to as well so they can give you a grounding of the joys of retail too. They\'re not getting that same kind of rush that they used to be of course again it goes down to certainly people chasing the same market. A red heart, we had a customer literally five miles from us and on Valentine\'s Day they would have a queue literally you know 50 yards and it\'s no exaggeration a 50-yard queue of people queuing up to buy red foil balloons on Valentine\'s Day and they were busy from two days before putting the balloons in a box and having them ready for their customers, pre-taking pre-orders as well. Now it\'s just another day with probably a 20 percent boost because even Marks and Spencers even Tesco\'s even name one Matalan, they all want to get involved in this because it\'s a quick kind of again quick sale for them. So the rather than selling a balloon that my retailer should be selling for two pound 50 for example, you getting a red heart for a pound from somewhere else so they\'re kind of again devaluing the market which makes it difficult. And we\'re all prepared for this now so we don\'t go as nuts as we used to in Valentine\'s Day or anything else. We kind of know it\'s going to be okay but not the most amazing thing since sliced bread. And it\'s just adapting to that so I would say when it comes to our bread and butter lines it is the everyday, it\'s the birthday, it’s the christenings, it\'s the anniversaries, it\'s the weddings are always gonna happen irrespective of what else is out there.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nOkay, okay, okay now that does make him a lot of sense and I certainly thinking just about my own family and the continuous stream of the Indians, birthdays, events, it\'s like non-stop. So it makes a lot of sense that\'s the actual core consistency rather then I think okay Valentine\'s Day must be the best but actually no it\'s as you said the bread and butter. Talking then of events, are there some particular kind of singular events that have been kind of stand out like moments for Go International that you know have been, yeah just talk to me a little bit about a couple of the events that you guys have been involved in that have been interesting.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nI think Halloween. When we first started in Halloween there was literally nothing in the UK. It\'s seriously nothing, we weren’t Trick or Treating or anything. And we\'d probably be lucky to sell even from a wholesale perspective...\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nHang on, so we weren\'t trick-or-treaters that blows my mind as someone, okay let\'s pivot a little bit. Talk to me a little bit about that then and how that has changed the business because Halloween today is huge. So could you talk to me a little bit about your experience of the growth and development of Halloween as a celebrated festival in England?\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nAgain thank you USA. We follow the USA on all these things they certainly took the lead and again because of the advent of internet and more interaction with people who have seen what was out there and growing our market, but again going back to the very beginning I think we would not, we wouldn\'t sell more than a couple of hundred Halloween balloons, foil balloons and that was about it. You dress up, you probably get a broomstick, you\'d probably get a witch\'s hat but if you look at what\'s out there that\'s totally exploded, totally exploded, so Halloween on a consistent basis we\'ve seen growth. In 2017 maybe not so much because again we\'re going back to everyone jumping on the bandwagon and everyone here going into Poundlands even going into any of the supermarkets, their shelves were actually chock-a-block with Halloween. So regrettably up all retailers haven\'t had that same shot in the arm that they used to get from something like Halloween. If it\'s smart and they\'re buying smart they can certainly still make an impact in their in their area but overall again it\'s another item that we\'ve seen start for absolutely zero skyrocketing to something you wouldn\'t believe and all some come not necessary crashing down for a sudden finding a level where we\'re just kind of doing okay with it.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nOkay, okay. Now Halloween, Halloween, Halloween, it blows my mind then. It sounds it sounds like the Americans are a little bit of, because they\'ve come up in a couple of our conversations when we were talking in regards to sales, we talked about Halloween and at the event, has the, is it fair then to say in the balloon industry that the Americans have been kind of the, have paved the way they\'ve been the pave makers, if you want from it.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nOh I\'m a shadow, whether it comes to who the leading manufacturers are, one of the leading trainers are, they\'re definitely all American and still are there are. Three probably, yeah three powerhouses at the moment which dominate the market they pretty much lead where we\'re going, what we\'re doing what the colors are going to be and we kind of follow and say thank you very much for the lead really.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nOkay, okay it\'s fascinating to me. What about then on the continent? What is the balloon market like outside of the UK? Because we\'ve just had a UK in kind of American focus really.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nI think the UK, we mentioned this last time has become a springboard for Europe for all that manufactures and it\'s been a good springboard and the joy of, I think the continent is where we were maybe 15-20 years ago where they\'re still developing their markets are still growing their markets and those who are involved are having an amazing time, it\'s like the gold rush where it\'s brand-new stuff everyone\'s being involved in and doing well because it\'s not involved in the way it has in the UK they\'re certainly on experiencing over saturation of the marketplace. So seeing more growth if you look at a growth curve, we\'re seeing more growth in Europe than we are in the UK right now. Because they\'re being allowed to do a week in the beginning go out there try new stuff and introduced the product to new markets. So absolutely Europe is a tremendous market for all of us.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nAnd is that for then someone who\'s coming you into the industry would you almost say that, you know the mainland Europe is a really interesting space. Do you, have you are there any particular adjustments you\'d need to make as a UK-based seller of balloons if you\'re trying to market to the French the Spanish, I\'ve got no idea really.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nYou know there are products out there especially Spanish because of the Spanish-American link as well and so there\'s lots of printed product which was fits into the Spanish market, we have birthday balloons in French. So if the market once said it can be produced very easily, it\'s never going to be an issue to do that. The other joy of Europe at the moment of course with BRX, the exchange rate, the euro to the pound ratio is really favored the European market so they\'re buying a lot more than they were before too and getting great prices right now.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nOkay that makes sense, okay. Final question, George before I love and leave you today. Can you, and well we\'ll talk about this in a lot further depth. What is thinking of the future talking about Europe and its growth curve, could you kind of give me what you think are a couple of like the trends of what you think the next 18, 24 to 36 months is going to look like in the balloon industry in general?\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nAnd you see a lot of consolidation, regrettably I can see numbers dwindling in respect to who the current players are and who they\'re going to be in year 12 might, well net 12 to 18 months down the line. Last year we saw two major manufacturers in their day, I\'m sorry two major wholesalers in their day to disappear off the face of the earth, they stopped trading. And it didn\'t even raise a blip on the Richter scale, you know once upon a time when companies of that size wins it will cause a problem. But it\'s been diluted extent now where no one has ultimate power. No one has that kind of ability to put that kind of strength on the market where they missed anymore. And because of that I think we\'re where I see it going is amalgamations, I see people working closer together and I see people obviously disappearing as well because they can\'t cope with what\'s happening out there. It\'ll be more streamlined. We are going to see the power players continue to dominate and kind of instill their brand, belief and what we should be doing on us and us having to kind of to a certain extent toe the line because if we don\'t or we do need them on our side, then again more problems arise. And so overall, I\'d say it\'s not necessarily gloomy as such but I definitely think that the changes we\'re going to see in the next 12 to 18 months and you\'ll be far more drastic than the changes we\'ve seen over the past 30 years.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nIs there then perhaps an opportunity for, is the key then to go specialist, if you\'re someone who\'s new is entering the market. Should you not enter the market at all because of the incumbents? So what\'s the advice then for someone who\'s like George\'s all these different kinds of products, there\'s all these suppliers. I know when I get into it but I don\'t I\'m not sure on my angle.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nOkay. We\'re very guilty of down selling rather than up selling. So if a newbie comes to us they want to spend and we\'ve had it many many times you want to spend a couple of grand with us and they want to kiss out of shop and they want to buy everything they possibly can. We always kind of down selling and we won\'t let them buy all the items they want to buy. We want them to understand their specific demographics and what they\'re trying to achieve. It\'s daunting to go into a into a wholesalers and look at all this stuff, all this kind of pretty sparkly stuff and know what\'s right for you. And so we\'re very conscious of making sure and to help them on their way making sure they\'re not one of these 90 to 95 failure rates in the first year. We\'re very conscious of making them understand that they need to know what their marketplace is. You know I don\'t believe this bad business is, I really don\'t I believe there\'s bad business owners. Because they haven\'t done due diligence they haven\'t looked into really what they want to do make them so many times it\'s just a whim they come into this because it\'s easy to get the get involved with. Then actually looking at what they want to achieve. So it\'s putting that horse behind you for a minute and putting the cart in front and of switching things around and then flipping things on their head and try to understand what are you trying to do in this industry, what are you coming to do, are you coming just to enter an industry because someone down the road has an amazing shop and I seem to be very very busy and they seem to be doing all the right things so you want a bit of that action. Are you doing that because you have a genuine passion for creativity and it\'s something that you can see a niché for? Have you done your homework? Have you research the area? Do you know if the demographics around you are kind of the older generation so they\'re looking for, here if you go to esport for example, if you go to esport it\'s like a retirement home in the UK. It\'s pointless going down there and having lots of Disney characters and Mickey and Mini and all the other stuff. Because you should be looking at anniversaries perhaps, you should be looking at something that fits in that market. So is it really is doing your homework before even spending a penny understanding who you looking to sell to.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nOkay, that sounds really senseable of when it sounds like someone who\'s has an understanding of course it has been through kind of the wars and the ups and downs. So everybody I guess the lesson here of course is do your homework, pick a particular demographic be excited nonetheless but really think about your positioning. Thank you George. I will see you, next week guys.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nThank you everybody. ', 'A Journey With Go International George Oustayiannis - Episode 3', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '235-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-06-26 14:33:48', '2018-06-26 13:33:48', '', 235, 'https://www.gointernational.co.uk/blog/235-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
