(238, 1, '2018-06-28 07:35:40', '2018-06-28 06:35:40', '<iframe width=\"643\" height=\"350\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/v5iroMGEP4o\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"autoplay; encrypted-media\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nHi guys welcome back to another episode of a journey with go international and I\'m back with George good morning George, how are you?\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nI\'m good how are you.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nGood I\'m good I wanted to talk to you today about NABAS what is it?\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nThe question what is NABAS, it\'s the Association for balloon artists and suppliers but it\'s far more than that now it\'s actually become more relevant to anyone that\'s in the party industry, whether you\'re a party decorator, whether you\'re a Balloon Twister, we\'re looking at incorporating in florists in there as well, so it\'s a growing Association that started 30 years ago to give support to the party industry.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nOkay perfect. So how would I, if I\'m someone for example that\'s just entering the industry what benefits would I get from NABAS or how does it work exactly.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nI think the most important benefit is a feeling of belonging, most people tend to join in our members for the insurance more than anything else because it\'s tremendously 1:01 important that you have pressed indemnity insurance, product liability insurance. So most members are really interested in insurance aspect of being remember.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nYeah.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nBut it goes far beyond that the most important part for me from my perspective is actually having a community that supports and works together and really grows us as an industry and an association.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nOkay, okay perfect and then where is it is it like a virtual 1:24 meet up is it face to face, do you guys do training or how does it work, how does it differ.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nAbsolutely everything um at least developing if we go back to number six its first started we had our 30th year / 30th year celebration last year individual operating for 30 years. I backed away and was absent for about 15 years of that because I really didn\'t like the direction it was going in it tended to kind of lose its way a little bit with certain manufacturers wanting to lead the way and certain other people having agendas 1:52, which weren\'t suitable to what we thought the industry should be doing. So it was in need of a great shake-up. So about two years ago I became involved I was asked to come back, I said no I was asked again, I said no and then the deal was i\'ve come back for three months and really helped the Association 2:06 and look at ways we could improve what it was doing and its appeal within the industry. So it really was in a very poor say two years ago.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nOkay.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nMy three months was interesting, I ended up literally upsetting every committee member and Sackman 2:21 will or seen him leave because I really didn\'t feel they were doing what the members needed. So I wasn\'t mr. Popular probably not mister looking now but it was something that there they needed to understand that this had to survive. I didn\'t want to see novice as the original Association disappearing into the quagmire 2:38, I really thought it had a place in our industry and more importantly a place of support for all its members, and they were getting nothing for their money apart from the insurance. So we wanted to give him a lot more than that the three months has now turned into two years regrettably 2:51 the chairman at the time he did pass away which is very sad a very guy that had a good relationship with and so all of a sudden I was left of being there on my own at sector 2:59 got rid of the entire committee and there I was wi