(251, 1, '2018-07-13 08:56:10', '2018-07-13 07:56:10', '<iframe width=\"643\" height=\"400\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/8RNHHTOLNdY\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"autoplay; encrypted-media\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nHey guys, welcome back to Episode 8 of a Journey of Go International with George Oustayiannis and myself Deepak. I presume it\'s time I gave myself a name. No that is my name is what my mother called me. We were giggling because George was wagging his finger. I\'m sure is that the first time he\'s done that because I got the episode number wrong, we are two months into this now apparently which is pretty cool and for the whole of the two months George has been wearing these very interesting rugby tops and it\'s kind of being a running conversation and George could you share with the world, what if any career you\'ve had in rugby? Or what is your pension before for these annoying rugby tops you wear?\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nWell, I love my rugby tops it’s very comfortable in the wind. So it\'s better than the shirt or a pullover I just like rugby tops and yeah I am from rugby initially, rugby school area. We did play rugby at school we didn\'t have soccer or football in our days it was purely rugby. I did captain a team out and in my school days but I hated it with a passion, so I was always make excuses of why I couldn\'t place then what I have cauliflower ears. But yeah I mean I just find it very comfortable.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nAbsolutely, and so you hated rugby yet you maintain wearing the shirts through the ages I see.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nYeah, it’s a love-hate relationship, I like the fashion but not the actual effort gone real.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nWell talking about stuff that\'s glutton for punishment, what has kept you in the industry? I mean we were just talking about the fact that you\'re talking to a lot of people that are scared by the competition or perhaps overwhelmed I mean you know name your adjective, what\'s kept you around? Why don\'t you, you know you\'ve made enough living yourself, you could probably wrap up shop and live relatively comfortably. What keeps you here after all this time?\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nWell it was my birthday yesterday which is actually a horrid, horrid day.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nHappy birthday, happy birthday Mr. Oustayiannis, how old are you?\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nNone of your business, it\'s also my birthday today because I\'m a leap year baby so I had two birthdays.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nOh amazing.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nToday was better until I had just talked to you but yes this is a nightmare. We started off with a three hour sit on a motorway.. Yeah, then we ended up losing car keys which I still can\'t find mine. Then we were going to drive to London for my birthday evening we jumped in the car and probably for the first time in 15 years of having a Range Rover it\'s the first time I really needed a Range Rover for this weather. Drove around the corner and the indicator started flashing that there was a tire issues like to go back home, get into another car. So it was quite a quite a horrendous journey in London last night with the weather but yeah I\'m back now and having fun, so yeah I guess so many entry to love challenges. You do ask these questions and I really don’t have time to think about which is good I guess but I think I do this mainly because I do really love it. I really enjoy the industry and some of the relationships I\'ve made within it as well are going to be lifelong relationships even when the doors that go closed or something else happens I don\'t know. And it\'s something that because I was in it at the very beginning, because it was something that I really do believe that we helped create and put on the maps when there wasn\'t a balloon industry or party industry in the UK. And something I\'m very passionate about and it\'s something I also get very vocal about when I see stuff going on but I really hate with a passion as well. So I can\'t see me changing just yet, I still think I\'m young enough for a few more years of fun inside of me. So I\'m not quite ready to close the doors. Well, no I still enjoy it. I still like the lights coming on in the morning, I still like seeing the interaction with the customers, immensely, it’s just something that I like.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nI mean what is it weather that we could all do or what is it the offer to perhaps the business owners, it’s kind of weathered I presume the industry.\r\n\r\n<strong>George: </strong>\r\nHaha, simple poetry\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nI was thinking of a wonderful additive and I was like, “Deepak key beauty you found it”, whether it looks body and mind. Happy birthday, twice over.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nOne of those that views this is my mother I can\'t swear at you.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nThank you George’s Mum.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nMy staff loves it when she comes here because I say I\'m naughty words she still wacks me around the head and they\'re actually in hysterics I can\'t believe my mum still hitting me at my wedded age. Oh what can I tell others, you know it\'s so easy to get into and so easy to get out on our scope of interest is switched from one thing to the other. We always believe that the grass is greener on the other side, you don\'t, I think for most people, I don\'t think they\'re hungry enough in a sense of they\'ve got to see through. There\'s always something else they can do and I guess if they don\'t hit millionaire status within three weeks these days they\'re thinking they\'re a failure. We\'re wanting this immediate gratification we are all expecting to open our doors or open our website the minute we do that. It\'s successful milk and honey but no one really realizes at the first one, two, three, five years. It can be nothing but a learning curve where we consistently keep hitting ourselves over the head at times or wondering why we\'re doing this. In a very beginning it’s so easy for me to give you many times in the beginning back to the close the doors and walked away from this.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nDo you think that, before we move on from that point it\'s really interesting because it\'s kind of resonates with an experience that I\'ve had with, you know I\'m 31 millennial and there\'s people that are younger than myself as well that are coming up and I feel that the media really represents what it takes to be successful. Is this a challenging you come up against the, you know a 19 year old kid does seven figures, 22 year old kid or I say kids you know inverted commas. I mean where do you think or no rather, do you think that the road to success is harder today as hard as it was other unrealistic expectations? Talk about this that whole space of kind of the false expectations of what it takes to succeed.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nWow. Success is with him always irrespective of, I can\'t think of an industry where we couldn\'t find someone that successful in it. Whether they\'re selling buttons, whether they\'re selling ice creams on the pier, whether they\'re selling royalties, whether, whatever they\'re selling there\'s always gonna be someone that does it well that makes a lot of money out of it, and there\'s always going to be a whole list of people on the side that failed in the blaming the product are not themselves and time and time again is, we’re our worst competitor, we’re our worst enemy, we\'re the ones that self-sabotage. Because it is the media that lead us to believe that everything is fallible so quickly. We see these young 19 and 21 year olds doing tremendously well and there will always be those people do well. What the internet age has given us is access to a whole world people out there who are willing to kind of interact with us and some do better than others. And I’m familiar with several in the States right now, again who are making six, seven figure incomes when it comes in the past two years purely by playing with things like Bitcoin for example others are developing an app on the phone which is suddenly taken over. So who could believe would sit on a train we don\'t want to play Angry Birds. It\'s just you know there are so many opportunities open to us that make tremendously good incomes for us but how many failed entrepreneurs are there? How many people made these ups and done nothing with them one still sitting home frustrate them. You\'re blaming the world rather than blaming a few other things maybe they should be doing themselves.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nAbsolutely, I think that that reflects misrepresentation that every success is like a hundred thousand failures. Okay, so could you profile an example of kind of the typical person that you see coming into the industry now? Is it anyone and everyone do you see like a lot younger wave of people coming in because they\'re like right, we can take this online and we can do this and do that? Has the shape of the person that\'s coming into the balloon industry changed, with the age of the internet or not really?\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nShape within even more not so diet conscious these days. I think the balloon industry has really been women dominated in the sense of those are actually at the front line. Yes there\'s are a number of guys in there some great trainers and some great decorators as well, but it\'s still very much female oriented. It\'s very creative and women are more creative than men as a rule. I think also it attracts more of a female clientele in the beginning that there\'s a male clients, it\'s gotten elements of, you know my parents were told in the beginning my parents were always embarrassed to say their son sells balloons, as it is not a very macho job to do, but it does have that creative element to it which does attract the wide female audience which is probably be the reason I stay here. I think it is a whole cross of people, you know if you came through these conventions which particular past and you see the people are there it\'s anything from 19 to 90. And there\'s some weird and wonderful characters within those 19 to 90 spans, it certainly isn\'t, you can\'t pigeonhole. You wouldn\'t actually look at them and easily kind of figure out why they why they\'re doing until you start talking to them.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nHow do in your experience people first typically have their first engagement with this industry in general and then decide, you know I\'d like to have a crack at this?\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nThing is everyone has a different story whether it\'s someone who\'s worked in a party shop or a balloon shop or a card shop that sells balloons, whether it\'s someone has been to a wedding or an event that seemed losing it there and thought I think I could do this quite well. Whether it\'s something that someone\'s going to a deeper level and been to an exhibition and seen a company there selling product that they can relate to, everyone has a different journey.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nOkay, okay. Now that does makes sense. Do balloon catalogs still exist? I, you know when you used to get like all the catalogs, is there one for the balloon industry as well?\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nThat sells product, absolutely all the manufacturers have their catalogs, yeah. Whether it\'s a Qualatex or monogram or unique or yeah, absolutely Sympatex, yes.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nOh my God, next video you have to show it to me.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nYeah okay.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nDo you have one?\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nYeah, absolutely, I’ve got them everywhere. You want me to get you one? Do you want to see a catalog?\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nI would like to see a catalog. The idea that catalogs still exists fascinate me. So those who are listening, George, no he\'s back, he\'s back.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nYeah, no brand preference or anything. This will get me an additional brownie point. Here we have a catalog that is full of lovely images, in fact this is over 250 pages worth of catalog just from one manufacturer, this is just one. I have a larger one, I have a smaller one, so yeah absolutely. We still have a printed format.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nAre they still used as part of your buying process? I know, do you look it up online or how does it..\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nIf you are going into a shop, just a standard retail shop at the moment and the person serving you wanted to show you what was available, very few shops you know with a pair of PC and allow you access the PC. Prices could be on there for example, so they\'ll show you a catalog will let you choose something from images there. There’s a color scheme, if you can have idea what colors are available for your events. So they really do have a purpose as a very valuable selling tool.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nAmazing. We must do an episode talking about the offline strategies that you still use today that are helpful to your business because that\'s pretty interesting. And I know your partner Lucilla for example, she has a shop. Does she for example, because I\'ve always thought that flyer is still effective, very effective for local based businesses, is that something that her business does or would do or is do you consider that not effective with, as a means of jamming up customers for local level.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nIt implies that usually there\'s no party shops between the party industry now for approximately 20 years. It\'s again I kind of it shows my tenacity not giving up she wouldn\'t buy off me for 20 years. ended up having to date removing with her before she bought off me, that’s how kind of, you know if I\'ve got a bit between my teeth and I\'ve got to get that customer, whatever it takes we get the customer. But yeah she\'s had successful businesses in major shopping centers, she\'ve been in the Lakeside Shopping Center at the moment she\'s in the Harlow shopping center pride that she wasn\'t that one down the road in Hatfield. So always in prominent locations with good footfalls. And I am a fan of fliers? The problem with the party in the stream and a lot of people we believe that the fliers are working if they hand out 10,000 fliers, now we\'ve got you know a stream of businesses at that time. The thing with party more than anything else is with a flyer, you might not be hitting your target audience at the time they\'re interested in knowing what you do. So you know everyone we\'ve talked about this before, everyone has a party, everyone has a birthday. There\'ll always be a time where you will be of relevance to a potential customer, it\'s just hitting them consistently or hitting them at the right time when it\'s suddenly bing.. I remember a flyer or you know I\'m off to the store because of and it\'s not purely, it must never just purely be one pillar to your business. You know flyers alone are totally I would say waste of time but they\'re not going to do it for you. There\'s got to be very specific ways of attracting customers. As from Lucilla\'s perspective the advantages that she is on a very busy thoroughfare where you\'re getting lots of passing trade continually. The downside of that obviously if you\'re a town specification wrapping has the card factories and the Clinton Cards and The Pound store is a stone\'s throw away, which create different challenges as well so. It\'s never a one size fits all but yes everything that\'s available there as a possible tool to market, you\'ve got to use these days.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nOkay, perfect, that’s makes a lot of sense. Let\'s finish up with a final question which is, what is the number one marketing advice or tip you\'d give to someone who says George, I\'ve got all of these balloons now how the frick do I sell them?\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nOkay, start with the people you know. It\'s most easy to sell to those you know to, compared to creating a new audience. So there\'s no embarrassment in going to friends and family who you know have birthdays coming up. The downside is never the problem ends and family has always expect huge discounts. If they respect you they\'ll realize it\'s a new business they won\'t want this huge discount. Do make a profit from they want don\'t do it for nothing. But use your existing know list and create a no list and sit down with a blank piece of paper and write down every single person you know. From the people you know let\'s talk to them and see who they know and grow your list from there, don\'t make it difficult just go back to basics with a pen and paper and start writing down contact lists.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nI don\'t think that people thirty or younger do that enough today to be honest with you. Everyone wants to go after some new funky person via a pic so and it\'s like hang on you already know all of these other people and they probably by okay, perfect, fantastic. Alright, Thank You George, episode 8 we\'re done.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nLet me do mine as well.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nNo today with this echo my friend. See you guys.\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nTake care. ', 'A Journey With Go International | George Oustayiannis | Episode 8', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'journey-with-go-international-george-oustayiannis-episode-8', '', '', '2018-08-29 16:56:44', '2018-08-29 15:56:44', '', 0, 'https://www.gointernational.co.uk/blog/?p=251', 0, 'post', '', 0),
