(254, 1, '2018-07-16 09:04:57', '2018-07-16 08:04:57', '<iframe width=\"643\" height=\"400\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/oCmTiwJNayY\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"autoplay; encrypted-media\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nHey guys, welcome back to another episode of a journey with go international. I say this intro all the time. George, hello, hi. George the six has asked me not to mention the rugby shirt. George welcome back, I know that you\'re in Barcelona for a couple of days. So what were you doing in Barcelona and because I saw the pictures they looked really good but if I\'m being honest as much as I\'m involved that didn\'t truly appreciate what the point of this convention was. So can you take it from the top?\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nYeah it’s just really we were there promoting NABAS in the industry and working together with our European colleagues just to show what can be done with balloons all the stuff takes it to a different level. But it\'s just the artistry at the end of the day Art\'s something that\'s appreciated in many ways. The majority of our customers aren\'t ever going to want to go down that route because of the time and cost constraints, but it really highlights what can be done. And Seba the European event in Barcelona has been doing for four years now. It started with 35 members four years ago and this year they\'ve pulled in about a hundred and fifty from all over Europe. And the energy was tremendous, it was a great group of people made some superb friends. Learned some great tricks and techniques as well. So yeah well it was a worthwhile trip.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deepak:</strong>\r\nIt sounds really good and honestly maybe some of the pictures were amazing. I was like wow I mean you know it made you look it made you look good which was mind-blowing for me. Seriously, some of the things that they can do with balloons and I think this comes back to the, for me as part of this process of these nine interviews that we\'ve had I feel I\'m beginning to get a better sense of the industry at large. And I\'m beginning to appreciate perhaps some of the challenges of someone such as yourself has with kind of Joe Bloggs who comes in onto the high street and says you know, it isn\'t apples and oranges, apples and apples what I get in Poundland or Argos or whatever it might be is the same as really what I could get from you. And I\'m realizing more and more that really isn\'t, not only from a product standpoint in terms of what can be done, but also of course the service and in the information and stuff. And I guess kind of, my question is, God, I guess what I\'m saying is I empathize with the fact that I\'m realizing how much scope there is and I guess the question I want to then ask is how can, how can someone wh is coming into the industry who has to compete with this perception that people have with have all kind of the balloon industry. How can they overcome that? How can they get around that? What is kind of your advice?\r\n\r\n<strong>George:</strong>\r\nI think I want to take you on a different tangent today. Basically my frustration with the industry and again, you quite rightly say it\'s what people perceive it to be on what they know, I think this week is one of tremendous frustration because we\'re having more issues with environmentalists and balloons in general. Our only members are confused of what\'s going on and they don\'t know where to turn on who to ask for advice. There\'s mixed messages coming through, the latest as of state in Melbourne which they\'re claiming is now banned balloons completely from its state and you can\'t just be seeing sold selling balloons or balloons or releasing balloons and it\'s not strictly true and I just want to get the message across of what is actually happening out there. And really kind of educate not only those that feel we\'re doing the damage but also those that should know better within our industry. But believe that if we giving is not even the right word but it\'s fear tactics are coming in with professionals who should know better. That they think that if we suddenly say to the environmentalist, look guys we won\'t ever have balloon releases again can we please do everything else that this problem will go away. I want to kind of spend a minute or two talking to you about how bad this is getting. In 2016 or as a petition now to create that petition is quite easy. You get five people who agree with you, you submit a petition to the government. If the petition lobby agrees with it they\'ll allow you to post a petition online, if you get to 10,000 signatures on the petition then it deserves a government answer. If you get to a hundred thousand signatures on a government petition then it should be read out in Parliament and answered in Parliament. In 2016 the environmentalists had their, one of many provisions but the first petition they\'ve got about 219 signatures because it was to ban balloon releases, and they\'re also talking about the problems with helium and how what a finite resource it is and we shouldn\'t be using in balloons. We got this a week or so ago so what we\'re going to the factory using a different kind of helium, such 1960s didn\'t do too well. They came back at us again in 2017 and this time they\'ve got more traction and got 2197 signatures. Again not really enough to even get a government response let alone having read in Parliament. So they then come up with a new one a new one is, sky lanterns and balloon releases in the same category. Now all of a sudden you know we are totally as an association as not as a company as well, we\'re totally against sky lanterns we see the problem with sky lanterns is releasing into the air and the problems that can cause not even wildlife but the fire implications and everything else. However because they went to the trouble of now classing us in the same bracket as a fire skylights going for the sky, they\'ve managed to get four to nine thousand signatures, so you can see these big Corrections improving. They\'re still very well short of the hundred required for it to be read in Parliament, however with the ten thousand plus that they have received now it did get a government reply. And the government reply went back to the 2013 report which is an independent study carried out, which quite clearly states that the government are happy with the current procedures in place, it is being monitored but at the moment we don\'t pose a threat. Now if the environmentalists work with us, I would go one further and say look I want to work with you guys environmentalist people and I want to stop sky lanterns because I actually see a problem with that. They\'re not getting the traction and they\'re getting lots of traction lots of great headline grabbing stuff, but they\'ve only got two forty-nine thousand and I said in eight days time, ten days time, I\'m sorry we\'re on the 8th of March, on the 18th of March the petition is closed. So they need to get 51,000 petitions in 8 days, 10 days they\'re not going to do that. So again it\'s not really in Parliament. So what they coming at us now with is littering. Littering is a completely different law, I think littering, I can\'t number the exact figures or the or what it falls on there is some European convention. That states if you\'re dropping litter or causing a litter scenario that them as an issue. So they\'re now saying that a balloon release represents litter because what goes up must come down. This is going to be the new traction point now because they can actually see that litter is going to be something that we\'re going to have a problem defending. We\'ve got people in our industry and these are professionals. These are guys who, yeah once upon a time you had to do an apprenticeship before you call yourself a wholesaler now you just have a wall shelf and cell volume in your wholesaler. And this is my frustration that the lack of education within our industry let alone outside our industry. People are meant to help you and educate you and help you understand what\'s going on out there. A kind of carrying around saying well we can\'t do this, we\'ve got to give you non balloon releases then they\'ll leave us alone everything else, which they won\'t. Because Australia is now seen like, i\'ve spoken to many many groups, and i\'ve spoken to the equivalent of NABAS and Australia and Riesling 07:36 as well and because they don\'t have releases in Australia and they\'ve animal because 07:40 Australia, the next now is anything to do with balloons. The state in question wants to ban balloons completely. Not from the entire town as in you can never buy them again, but from public places public own places, parks etc. So it\'s not as widespread as they\'re trying to make out. As well as that they are escalating it where the course our members let the only industry is getting a little bit of flack right now, and being verbally abused at best. But even some of the retailer\'s deciding not to do balloons in their centers again, you know talking to the guys in Australia early this morning, there is a shop that is always used to balloon modular. So he just makes balloons, twist balloons and gives you a dog or a donkey or whatever. He will have his license revoked in a matter of weeks now and they\'re not going to use in the centre. So it\'s a problem for our industry that must be addressed, it\'s not, i\'ve been in this for 30 years and 30 years i\'ve never done a balloon release. It\'s not because I don\'t think that environmentally friendly or it\'s just something i\'ve never done. But what I am trying to do is take a kind of a different view and trying to protect the industry as a whole and I really want to work with these people I\'m currently working with a group down the Portsmouth way. That supports with its Cornwall. And we liaison i\'ve given them balloons make look at what they are, what they do and I